# Git sync across laptops

GitHub `main` is the single source of truth — not local files on any one machine.

## Start of every session (before reading or editing code)

1. Run `git fetch origin` then `git status` to see if the local branch is behind `origin/main`.
2. If behind, or if the user may have pushed from another laptop, run `git pull origin main` (use `git pull --rebase origin main` if there are only unpushed local commits and a fast-forward is not possible).
3. If pull fails due to local uncommitted changes, tell the user and help them stash, commit, or discard before pulling — do not overwrite their work silently.
4. After a successful pull, briefly confirm the repo is up to date (e.g. "Pulled latest from GitHub; on main, up to date").

Do this even when the user does not mention sync — they work from multiple laptops.

## During work

- Do not assume local files are current without checking git status first.
- If `git status` shows divergence from `origin/main` mid-session, pause and sync before continuing.

## End of session (after making changes)

- Only commit when the user explicitly asks.
- After changes are committed, remind the user to push to `origin main` so other laptops and Netlify stay current.
- Deploy path: push to `main` triggers Netlify deploy.

## Remote

- Repository: `https://github.com/PeakHealthPharmacy/PeakHealth-Website.git`
- Default branch: `main`
